atever is experienced is easy to meditate upon, and th=\r\nat which is not experienced can be difficult to meditate upon. Everyone can=\r\n meditate upon the light of the Sun. This is why this meaning for the Gayat=\r\nri mantra is always taken first. &lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;vareNyam=A0=\r\n=3D whatever we can ask=A0/ desire. Through all karmas and upaasanaas, what=\r\never fruits we may ask for is vareNyam. =93Savitaa&quot; is the fruit of al=\r\nl karmas ... this is taught in the Chandogya Upanishad. [ A long explanatio=\r\nn follows, which is omitted here ].=A0 We meditate upon the splendor of the=\r\n sun, which is vareNyam.&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;We\n meditate upon that=\r\n Savitaa (yaH) who impels (prachodayaat) our (naH) thoughts (dhiyaH). He bl=\r\nesses us with subtle eyesight. Without his light, we would not be able to d=\r\nistinguish different objects. This is explained in the Aitaterya Upanishad=\r\n=A0=93The sun, having become eyesight, entered the eyes=94. He thus blesses=\r\n all living beings. &lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;----&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;d=\r\niv&gt;Sent from Windows Mail&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n     =\r\n\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n   =\r\n  \n\n    \n    &lt;div style=3D&quot;color:rgb(255,255,255)&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n  \n\n\n=\r\n\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n&lt;br&gt;\n\n    \n    \n&lt;br&gt;\n\n\n=\r\n\n\n&lt;div style=3D&quot;color:white&quot; width=3D&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/bloc=\r\nkquote&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n     \n\n    \n   